    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2888122094" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2888122094" />
    <a title="Henk" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/76202320-henk"><img alt="Henk" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1557871304p2/76202320.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2888122094?book_show_action=true">Mar 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Henk" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Henk" href="/user/show/76202320-henk">Henk</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9789403149202" href="/book/show/50876556-de-pest">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/76202320-henk?shelf=owned-e-books">owned-e-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2888122094" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer700583166926724185"><b>Very understated, impersonal, plain writing, that drives the universal themes home.<br/>Deeply human and showing a believe in the overall good of humanity, without closing eyes to our weaker instincts. - 4 stars</b><br/><i>All I maintain is that on this earth there are pestilences and there are victims, and it&apos;s up to us, so far as possible, not to join forces with the pestilences.</i><br/><br/>A compelling and surprisingly quick classic in these strange times. <br/><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11989.The_Plague' title='The Plague by Albert Camus' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Plague</a> reads like a fever dream.<br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1441120420i/16065846._SY540_.png' width='164' height='226' alt='description' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>The story of Oran is quite si</span>
  <span id="freeText700583166926724185" style="display:none"><b>Very understated, impersonal, plain writing, that drives the universal themes home.<br>Deeply human and showing a believe in the overall good of humanity, without closing eyes to our weaker instincts. - 4 stars</b><br><i>All I maintain is that on this earth there are pestilences and there are victims, and it's up to us, so far as possible, not to join forces with the pestilences.</i><br><br>A compelling and surprisingly quick classic in these strange times. <br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11989.The_Plague" title="The Plague by Albert Camus" rel="nofollow noopener">The Plague</a> reads like a fever dream.<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1441120420i/16065846._SY540_.png" width="164" height="226" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>The story of Oran is quite similar to the later novel <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40495148.Blindness" title="Blindness by José Saramago" rel="nofollow noopener">Blindness</a> of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/1285555.Jos__Saramago" title="José Saramago" rel="nofollow noopener">José Saramago</a>, but without the supernatural touch. <br>This non-descript town in Algeria is overrun by rats dying in the streets and houses, and soon after the government needs to deal with a full scale bubonic plague and we have scenes reminiscent of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/4178.Cormac_McCarthy" title="Cormac McCarthy" rel="nofollow noopener">Cormac McCarthy</a>'s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6288.The_Road" title="The Road by Cormac McCarthy" rel="nofollow noopener">The Road</a> in terms of bleakness. <br><br>The development of the plague very uncanningly mirrors what our 21st century governments do now in the midst of the Covid-19 outbreak. First there is denial, then there are commissions and deliberations on the impact on the economy, then measures are taken and doctors are finally heard when it is already too late to contain the outbreak. <br>And then Oran enters a wartime economy while the town is waiting for the quarantaine to lift.<br><br>The population in general handles the deaths quite well. <br>Yes there is superstition, there are smugglers, helplessness, people try to break out. <br>The escape plot feels very much like a book of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/5223.Franz_Kafka" title="Franz Kafka" rel="nofollow noopener">Franz Kafka</a>, especially when the process must be repeated due to a slight timing difference. <br>But to balance this, there are also voluntary help troops, people who aid doctors doing their jobs, and medics working around the clock to stem the rise of the plague. <br>We are presented with incredibly touching scenes from doctor Rieux' perspective, who is fighting the plague and is confronted with dying children and separated family members.<br> <br>It's eerily familiar to these times of Covid-19, and very well captured by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/957894.Albert_Camus" title="Albert Camus" rel="nofollow noopener">Albert Camus</a>. Even though the novel itself was maybe more meant as a symbol for the threat of fascism rising once again after World War II than the depiction of a factual plague, it definitely feels uncanny to read this classic in our current day and age. <br>The book makes you think who you are in a crisis and if you have the integrity to do the right thing. If the characters were a bit less representations of ideas (and if a convincing female character would be thrown in the mix), I would have found The Plague a solid 5 star read. <br>Still this is a timeless book that had a surprisingly positive message on humanity and it's capacity to deal with adversity. <br>Highly recommended in these troubling times.<br><br><b>Quotes (in Dutch):</b><br><i>In Oran hebben de bewoners net als elders zo weinig tijd en denken zo weinig na, dat ze van elkaar houden omdat het moet en zonder het te weten.<br><br>Stompzinnigheid is een stugge volhouder, zoals we zouden merken als we niet voortdurend aan onszelf dachten<br><br>Ik ben niet blij dat ik wegga, maar om een nieuw leven te beginnen hoef je niet blij te zijn<br><br>Wat wilde dat zeggen, medelijden? Natuurlijk had hij dat, maar daar schoot niemand iets mee op<br><br>Je krijgt genoeg van medelijden als het nutteloos is.<br><br>Maar deze rotziekte! Zelfs de mensen die er niet aan lijden lopen ermee rond<br><br>Want zo wordt gesuggereerd dat fraaie acties alleen waarde hebben doordat ze schaars zijn en doordat de mens meestal handelt uit slechtheid en nonchalance<br><br>Overigens was dat volgens iemand als dokter Rieux juist het probleem: gewenning aan wanhoop is erger dan de wanhoop zelf<br><br>Ik weet dat ik tot dat moment niets meer beteken voor deze wereld en dat ik met het afzweren van het doden mezelf heb veroordeeld tot een onherroepelijke ballingschap. Anderen zullen de geschiedenis maken. Ik weet ook dat ik waarschijnlijk geen oordeel kan vellen over die anderen. Ik mis iets om bewust een moordenaar te kunnen zijn. Het is dus geen superioriteit. Maar momenteel accepteer ik mezelf zoals ik ben, ik heb bescheidenheid geleerd. Het enige wat ik beweer is dat er op deze aarde plagen en slachtoffers zijn en dat je zoveel mogelijk moet voorkomen aan de kant van de plaag te staan. Dat lijkt misschien een tikkeltje simpel, maar simpel of niet, ik weet dat het waar is.<br><br>...hoe rechtvaardig het is dat, althans van tijd tot tijd, degenen die genoeg hebben aan de mens en zijn armzalige, ontzettende liefde, beloond worden met blijdschap<br><br>De anderen zeggen: “De pest, we hebben aan de pest geleden” en ze zouden er bijkans een lintje voor vragen. Maar wat is de pest eigenlijk helemaal? Het leven, meer niet.’</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="700583166926724185" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


