<span id="freeTextContainer4970329323565978866">The Plague is one of my favourite novels of 2019. My head is buzzing from all the proffered ideas, and the story and writing are excellent too. I also loved the fact that the stranded opera company kept performing <i>Orpheus and Eurydice</i>* Perfect! <br/><br/>Anything else that I might say about this outstanding novel is bound to be trite nonsense. Fortunately there are many splendid reviews of it.<br/>#<br/>#<br/>Although I have read L’étranger/The Outsider in both French and English I forgot what a brilliant author Albert </span>
  <span id="freeText4970329323565978866" style="display:none">The Plague is one of my favourite novels of 2019. My head is buzzing from all the proffered ideas, and the story and writing are excellent too. I also loved the fact that the stranded opera company kept performing <i>Orpheus and Eurydice</i>* Perfect! <br /><br />Anything else that I might say about this outstanding novel is bound to be trite nonsense. Fortunately there are many splendid reviews of it.<br />#<br />#<br />Although I have read L’étranger/The Outsider in both French and English I forgot what a brilliant author Albert Camus is - that is until now. I do have La Peste, the French edition of The Plague on my bookshelves at home, and I might just have to read it.<br /><br />*And of course I listened to Orfeo ed Euridice (the Gluck version - Sylvia McNair and Derek Lee Ragin), and I might have to play Joseph Haydn’s version too (Joan Sutherland and Nicolai Gedda).</span>
